# Tierless

**Make a cheaper model perform a tier above its size.** Tierless is a library of composable
discipline skills for AI coding agents (Claude Code, Cursor, Codex). A frontier model's advantage
isn't raw intelligence — it's process discipline: decompose before coding, verify incrementally,
adversarial review, loop-until-dry. Smaller, cheaper models are fast at execution but skip the
"think first" steps, so they ship more bugs and rework. Tierless packages that implicit discipline
as explicit, opt-in skills, so a smaller model follows the same process — and closes the tier gap.

The name says the goal: no tiers. The cheap model and the frontier model produce work of the same
caliber, because the caliber lives in the process, not the weights.

## Does it actually work?

We measure it — see `eval/`. The harness runs each task three ways (cheap model bare / cheap model
+ skills / frontier model bare) and grades against objective "tells." First results
(`eval/results/SCORES.md`) are honest and mixed: one clean win where a skill closed the gap to the
frontier model, one case where a skill backfired, and several tasks where a modern cheap model is
already strong enough that the skills add little. Validation is ongoing, not assumed — that
measured-honesty is itself the differentiator in a crowded space.

## Why skills over system prompt

- Skills are opt-in per task, so you layer discipline where it matters (architecture, migrations,
  reviews) and skip it for trivial edits
- Skills are shareable across sessions — once defined, every session gets the discipline
- System prompt bloat is real; a 5000-word "be careful" prompt gets ignored at the margins

## Setup

```
./scripts/project-init
```

Creates `.claude/skills/` symlinks (so Claude Code discovers the skills) and `.claude/plans/`
(where skill artifacts — compositions, plans, verification reports — are written).

## The system

The entry point is **fable-discipline** — the router. It classifies each task into a tier
(trivial / medium / hard / project) and prescribes which skills to layer. For multi-session
projects, **build-loop** is the outer structure: phased delivery with hard entry/exit gates,
requiring the discipline pipeline inside each phase.

**Routing & structure:**
- fable-discipline — THE ENTRY POINT: tier classification, conditional lanes, loop-until-dry
- build-loop — outer loop for multi-session projects: phased delivery with exit gates

**Core pipeline** (engineering discipline, in order):
- requirements-elicitation — clarify the ambiguous ask before anything: restate with a done-condition
- compose — understand before designing: read the code, map architecture, mark assumptions
- plan-mode — design before building: scope, steps, edge cases, verification, rollback
- deconstruct — atomic steps (<50 lines), dependency-ordered, each with a pass condition
- verify — the exit gate: pass conditions, adversarial self-review, regression check

**Specialist disciplines** (same think-first process, applied to other crafts):
- debugging — hypothesis-driven root-cause hunting; no fix without a demonstrated cause
- refactoring — behavior-preserving chains of small green-to-green transformations
- code-archaeology — evidence before assumption in legacy code; Chesterton's Fence enforced
- api-design — contract-first interfaces; the contract outlives the implementation
- data-migration — expand/migrate/contract; reversible, rehearsed, verified by counting
- incident-response — mitigate first, diagnose second, fix third; no novel code under pressure
- code-migration — ports via strangler pattern: vertical slices, equivalence proven, old path deleted
- performance-optimization — profile first, one change per measurement, stop at the target number
- dependency-management — vet, pin, upgrade on cadence; every dependency has an exit plan
- human-code-review — altitude-first review, blocking/nit labels, critique code not coders
- version-control — atomic commits with why-messages; history as a debugging tool
- threat-modeling — design-time security: assets/attackers/boundaries modeled before code exists
- release-management — versions as contracts, enumerated cuts, flags with removal dates
- user-docs — reader-task documentation; every instruction executed before shipping
- tech-doc — design docs as decision instruments: problem before solution, steelmanned alternatives
- adversarial-review — independent bug hunt over a diff (six attack-vector categories)
- security-review — vulnerability pass keyed to the surfaces the change actually touches
- qa-testing — test plans designed from behavior contracts, validated by mutation
- naming — identifiers that communicate intent; conventions enforced before merge

**Domain disciplines** (the process the model skips in each domain — not knowledge it already has):
- ai-building — evals before prompts, structured output, failure paths designed as features
- ai-safety — agentic containment: least privilege by environment, action gates, bounded loops
- software-architecture — ADRs for hard-to-reverse decisions, boundaries by change-rate
- database-design — constraints in the DB, queries proven with EXPLAIN at realistic scale
- systems-programming — invariants first, fault injection, crash-consistency, sanitizers
- compiler-building — spec before code, staged pipeline, testing as half the work
- shell-scripting — strict mode, quoting, idempotency, escalate past plumbing
- infra-ops — everything as code, reversible deploys, observability before incidents
- cross-platform — differences cataloged, platform code quarantined, all targets tested

**Product & design disciplines:**
- roadmap — MVP / v1 / v2+ phasing with explicit out-of-scope lists
- estimation — reference-class sizing: ranges with named risks, never points
- ui-design — token systems, hierarchy, the five component states, accessibility floor
- ux-design — flow design before screen design; friction audits and error recovery
- icp-onboarding — the product's first-run path from signup to the customer's first win
- onboarding — developer onboarding: zero to first contribution in one session

The key insight: a frontier model's "mental discipline" is really just structured process enforced
by tooling. A smaller model can match it if the skills force the same steps. The system is
composable — full pipeline for hard work, deconstruct + verify for medium work, nothing for trivial
work. `skills/README.md` is the full index.

---

*Note: the router skill is currently filed as `fable-discipline` (a name from the project's origin).
Renaming it and scrubbing the remaining "Fable" references across 41 files is tracked as a separate
change — it touches every cross-reference, so it's done as its own verified task rather than inline.*
